rtPos + insertLen + remaining)\n\nSince we can only represent a single contiguous delete, the standard approach is to increase the delete length by the insert length, which would delete the inserted text too - but that's wrong because we want to preserve the insert.\n\nThe real solution is to either split the operation or handle it differently. Let me think about this more carefully...\n\nActually, looking at this from the perspective of the server-authoritative model:\n\n1. Server has \"ABCDEF\", version 0\n2. Client 1 sends: insert \"X\" at 3, version 0 → Server applies it → \"ABCXDEF\", version 1\n3. Client 2 sends: delete 2 at 2, version 0 → Must transform against insert \"X\" at 3\n\nThe delete [2, 4) in original covers C(2) and D(3). The insert is at position 3. After the insert, C is at 2, X is at 3, D is at 4. To delete C and D (original chars), we need to delete at [2,3) and [4,5). Since we can't represent two deletes, we need to either:\n\n1. Apply as two separate operations internally\n2. Delete [2, 5) which would also delete X - but that's wrong\n3. Keep the delete and handle it as [2, 2+3) = delete 3 chars? No, that deletes X too.\n\nThe cleanest approach for this scenario is to split the delete into two operations when an insert falls within the delete range. Let me update the OT transform to handle this by applying the operation in parts within the document manager.\n\nActually, a simpler pivot: Instead of trying to handle split deletes in the OT layer, I'll update the transform so that when a delete spans an insert point, the delete is adjusted to skip over the inserted characters. This means increasing the length by the insert length - but then we'd delete the inserted text too.\n\nThe correct OT transformation for delete vs insert where the delete spans the insert:\n- Position stays the same (before insert)\n- Length increases by the insert length\n\nWait, that would delete the inserted text. That's wrong.\n\nThe proper approach in standard OT: if 